Every edition of Terence that I have seen has some curious informa- tion on the nomenclature of the characters of Terence. Names had, no doubt, as they now have, their etymology, and certain general observa- tions respecting them may hold good3 as, for example, the common deri- vation of the names of slaves, male and female, from the countries from which slaves were generally obtained ; the names that were in vogue to distinguish courtezans from women of good position. But we can only laugh at the commentator, however ancient and respectable, who tells us that Simo was a name given to an acrimonious and suspicions old gentleman, because “ Simi fere sunt iracundi,'' or that another old gen-f tleman, Chremes, derives his name from χρέμπτεσθαι, enixe exspuere, for “ old men are often troubled with an inveterate cough,’' while curiously enough the same name is given in another play to a young man ; why, commentators wisely decline to say. Such investigatione are to be paralleled only by the pertinacity of the old commentatore on Horace in giving to every Lydia and Chloe apostrophized by the poet a local habitation and a history. We have no reason to suppose that. Terence or any other comic poet went so far in the esoteric application of their nomenclature. The Drama. has always had its regular reper- tory of names ae well as of dresses3 and we may as well endeavour to find a moral in the Guys and Amelias of the modern novel as in a Pamphilus, aMenedemus,'or a Simo.
